    <item>
      <title>Be professional in your work</title>
      <link>https://linguage.github.io/terencetao/career-advice/orig/be-professional-in-your-work/</link>
      <pubDate>Sun, 06 May 2007 19:03:51 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://linguage.github.io/terencetao/career-advice/orig/be-professional-in-your-work/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;https://linguage.github.io/terencetao/career-advice/zh/be-professional-in-your-work.zh/&#34;&gt;中文版本&lt;/a&gt;&#xA;&lt;div&#xA;  class=&#34;link-card group relative my-3 w-full overflow-hidden rounded-xl border border-[var(--lc-border,rgba(15,23,42,0.12))] bg-[var(--lc-bg,var(--card-bg,var(--surface,#ffffff))))] transition-shadow duration-150 hover:shadow-[var(--lc-shadow-hover,0_14px_30px_-18px_rgba(15,23,42,0.35))]&#34;&#xA;  data-url=&#34;https://terrytao.wordpress.com/career-advice/be-professional-in-your-work/&#34;&#xA;&gt;&#xA;  &lt;a&#xA;    class=&#34;link-card__fallback block px-4 py-3 text-sm font-medium text-[var(--lc-url,var(--link-color,#0e6a85))] underline-offset-4 hover:underline&#34;&#xA;    href=&#34;https://terrytao.wordpress.com/career-advice/be-professional-in-your-work/&#34;&#xA;    target=&#34;_blank&#34;&#xA;    rel=&#34;noopener&#34;&#xA;  &gt;&#xA;    https://terrytao.wordpress.com/career-advice/be-professional-in-your-work/&#xA;  &lt;/a&gt;&#xA;&lt;/div&gt;&#xA;&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;h1 id=&#34;be-professional-in-your-work&#34;&gt;Be professional in your work&lt;/h1&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Integrity without knowledge is weak and useless, and knowledge without integrity is dangerous and dreadful.&lt;br&gt;&#xA;&lt;em&gt;(Samuel Johnson, &amp;ldquo;Rasselas&amp;rdquo;)&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Take your duties and responsibilities seriously; being frivolous is fine with friends, but can be annoying for your colleagues, especially those who are busy with similar responsibilities.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Talk to your advisor</title>
      <link>https://linguage.github.io/terencetao/career-advice/orig/talk-to-your-advisor/</link>
      <pubDate>Sun, 06 May 2007 18:59:12 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://linguage.github.io/terencetao/career-advice/orig/talk-to-your-advisor/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;https://linguage.github.io/terencetao/career-advice/zh/talk-to-your-advisor.zh/&#34;&gt;中文版本&lt;/a&gt;&#xA;&lt;div&#xA;  class=&#34;link-card group relative my-3 w-full overflow-hidden rounded-xl border border-[var(--lc-border,rgba(15,23,42,0.12))] bg-[var(--lc-bg,var(--card-bg,var(--surface,#ffffff))))] transition-shadow duration-150 hover:shadow-[var(--lc-shadow-hover,0_14px_30px_-18px_rgba(15,23,42,0.35))]&#34;&#xA;  data-url=&#34;https://terrytao.wordpress.com/career-advice/talk-to-your-advisor/&#34;&#xA;&gt;&#xA;  &lt;a&#xA;    class=&#34;link-card__fallback block px-4 py-3 text-sm font-medium text-[var(--lc-url,var(--link-color,#0e6a85))] underline-offset-4 hover:underline&#34;&#xA;    href=&#34;https://terrytao.wordpress.com/career-advice/talk-to-your-advisor/&#34;&#xA;    target=&#34;_blank&#34;&#xA;    rel=&#34;noopener&#34;&#xA;  &gt;&#xA;    https://terrytao.wordpress.com/career-advice/talk-to-your-advisor/&#xA;  &lt;/a&gt;&#xA;&lt;/div&gt;&#xA;&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;h1 id=&#34;talk-to-your-advisor&#34;&gt;Talk to your advisor&lt;/h1&gt;&#xA;&lt;blockquote&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;It is the province of knowledge to speak and it is the privilege of wisdom to listen.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;(Oliver Wendell Holmes, &amp;ldquo;The Poet at the Breakfast Table&amp;rdquo;)&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/blockquote&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Your advisor is one of the best sources of guidance you have; not only in directly assisting you with your research topic, but in directing you (both explicitly and implicitly) to relevant researchers, conferences, publications, open problems, folklore, or other pieces of good mathematics. Your advisor also knows your situation well and can give career advice which is tailored to your specific strengths and weaknesses (unlike the &lt;strong&gt;generic advice&lt;/strong&gt; in these pages).&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>How to Disagree</title>
      <link>https://linguage.github.io/paul_graham/essays_en/disagree/</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://linguage.github.io/paul_graham/essays_en/disagree/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;→ &lt;a href=&#34;https://linguage.github.io/paul_graham/essays_zh/disagree/&#34;&gt;Chinese Version&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;div&#xA;  class=&#34;link-card group relative my-3 w-full overflow-hidden rounded-xl border border-[var(--lc-border,rgba(15,23,42,0.12))] bg-[var(--lc-bg,var(--card-bg,var(--surface,#ffffff))))] transition-shadow duration-150 hover:shadow-[var(--lc-shadow-hover,0_14px_30px_-18px_rgba(15,23,42,0.35))]&#34;&#xA;  data-url=&#34;https://www.paulgraham.com/disagree.html&#34;&#xA;&gt;&#xA;  &lt;a&#xA;    class=&#34;link-card__fallback block px-4 py-3 text-sm font-medium text-[var(--lc-url,var(--link-color,#0e6a85))] underline-offset-4 hover:underline&#34;&#xA;    href=&#34;https://www.paulgraham.com/disagree.html&#34;&#xA;    target=&#34;_blank&#34;&#xA;    rel=&#34;noopener&#34;&#xA;  &gt;&#xA;    https://www.paulgraham.com/disagree.html&#xA;  &lt;/a&gt;&#xA;&lt;/div&gt;&#xA;&#xA;&lt;h1 id=&#34;how-to-disagree&#34;&gt;How to Disagree&lt;/h1&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;March 2008&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;The web is turning writing into a conversation. Twenty years ago, writers wrote and readers read. The web lets readers respond, and increasingly they do—in comment threads, on forums, and in their own blog posts.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Many who respond to something disagree with it. That&amp;rsquo;s to be expected. Agreeing tends to motivate people less than disagreeing. And when you agree there&amp;rsquo;s less to say. You could expand on something the author said, but he has probably already explored the most interesting implications. When you disagree you&amp;rsquo;re entering territory he may not have explored.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Putting Ideas into Words</title>
      <link>https://linguage.github.io/paul_graham/essays_en/words/</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://linguage.github.io/paul_graham/essays_en/words/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;→ &lt;a href=&#34;https://linguage.github.io/paul_graham/essays_zh/words/&#34;&gt;中文版&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;div&#xA;  class=&#34;link-card group relative my-3 w-full overflow-hidden rounded-xl border border-[var(--lc-border,rgba(15,23,42,0.12))] bg-[var(--lc-bg,var(--card-bg,var(--surface,#ffffff))))] transition-shadow duration-150 hover:shadow-[var(--lc-shadow-hover,0_14px_30px_-18px_rgba(15,23,42,0.35))]&#34;&#xA;  data-url=&#34;https://www.paulgraham.com/words.html&#34;&#xA;&gt;&#xA;  &lt;a&#xA;    class=&#34;link-card__fallback block px-4 py-3 text-sm font-medium text-[var(--lc-url,var(--link-color,#0e6a85))] underline-offset-4 hover:underline&#34;&#xA;    href=&#34;https://www.paulgraham.com/words.html&#34;&#xA;    target=&#34;_blank&#34;&#xA;    rel=&#34;noopener&#34;&#xA;  &gt;&#xA;    https://www.paulgraham.com/words.html&#xA;  &lt;/a&gt;&#xA;&lt;/div&gt;&#xA;&#xA;&lt;h1 id=&#34;putting-ideas-into-words&#34;&gt;Putting Ideas into Words&lt;/h1&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;February 2022&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Writing about something, even something you know well, usually shows you that you didn&amp;rsquo;t know it as well as you thought. Putting ideas into words is a severe test. The first words you choose are usually wrong; you have to rewrite sentences over and over to get them exactly right. And your ideas won&amp;rsquo;t just be imprecise, but incomplete too. Half the ideas that end up in an essay will be ones you thought of while you were writing it. Indeed, that&amp;rsquo;s why I write them.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>The List of N Things</title>
      <link>https://linguage.github.io/paul_graham/essays_en/nthings/</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://linguage.github.io/paul_graham/essays_en/nthings/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;→ &lt;a href=&#34;https://linguage.github.io/paul_graham/essays_zh/nthings/&#34;&gt;中文版本&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;div&#xA;  class=&#34;link-card group relative my-3 w-full overflow-hidden rounded-xl border border-[var(--lc-border,rgba(15,23,42,0.12))] bg-[var(--lc-bg,var(--card-bg,var(--surface,#ffffff))))] transition-shadow duration-150 hover:shadow-[var(--lc-shadow-hover,0_14px_30px_-18px_rgba(15,23,42,0.35))]&#34;&#xA;  data-url=&#34;https://www.paulgraham.com/nthings.html&#34;&#xA;&gt;&#xA;  &lt;a&#xA;    class=&#34;link-card__fallback block px-4 py-3 text-sm font-medium text-[var(--lc-url,var(--link-color,#0e6a85))] underline-offset-4 hover:underline&#34;&#xA;    href=&#34;https://www.paulgraham.com/nthings.html&#34;&#xA;    target=&#34;_blank&#34;&#xA;    rel=&#34;noopener&#34;&#xA;  &gt;&#xA;    https://www.paulgraham.com/nthings.html&#xA;  &lt;/a&gt;&#xA;&lt;/div&gt;&#xA;&#xA;&lt;h1 id=&#34;the-list-of-n-things&#34;&gt;The List of N Things&lt;/h1&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;September 2009&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;I bet you the current issue of Cosmopolitan has an article whose title begins with a number. &amp;ldquo;7 Things He Won&amp;rsquo;t Tell You about Sex,&amp;rdquo; or something like that. Some popular magazines feature articles of this type on the cover of every issue. That can&amp;rsquo;t be happening by accident. Editors must know they attract readers.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Useful</title>
      <link>https://linguage.github.io/paul_graham/essays_en/useful/</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://linguage.github.io/paul_graham/essays_en/useful/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;→ &lt;a href=&#34;https://linguage.github.io/paul_graham/essays_zh/useful/&#34;&gt;中文版本&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;div&#xA;  class=&#34;link-card group relative my-3 w-full overflow-hidden rounded-xl border border-[var(--lc-border,rgba(15,23,42,0.12))] bg-[var(--lc-bg,var(--card-bg,var(--surface,#ffffff))))] transition-shadow duration-150 hover:shadow-[var(--lc-shadow-hover,0_14px_30px_-18px_rgba(15,23,42,0.35))]&#34;&#xA;  data-url=&#34;https://www.paulgraham.com/useful.html&#34;&#xA;&gt;&#xA;  &lt;a&#xA;    class=&#34;link-card__fallback block px-4 py-3 text-sm font-medium text-[var(--lc-url,var(--link-color,#0e6a85))] underline-offset-4 hover:underline&#34;&#xA;    href=&#34;https://www.paulgraham.com/useful.html&#34;&#xA;    target=&#34;_blank&#34;&#xA;    rel=&#34;noopener&#34;&#xA;  &gt;&#xA;    https://www.paulgraham.com/useful.html&#xA;  &lt;/a&gt;&#xA;&lt;/div&gt;&#xA;&#xA;&lt;h1 id=&#34;useful&#34;&gt;Useful&lt;/h1&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;How to Write Usefully&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;February 2020&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;What should an essay be? Many people would say persuasive. That&amp;rsquo;s what a lot of us were taught essays should be. But I think we can aim for something more ambitious: that an essay should be useful.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;To start with, that means it should be correct. But it&amp;rsquo;s not enough merely to be correct. It&amp;rsquo;s easy to make a statement correct by making it vague. That&amp;rsquo;s a common flaw in academic writing, for example. If you know nothing at all about an issue, you can&amp;rsquo;t go wrong by saying that the issue is a complex one, that there are many factors to be considered, that it&amp;rsquo;s a mistake to take too simplistic a view of it, and so on.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Write Like You Talk</title>
      <link>https://linguage.github.io/paul_graham/essays_en/talk/</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://linguage.github.io/paul_graham/essays_en/talk/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;→ &lt;a href=&#34;https://linguage.github.io/paul_graham/essays_zh/talk/&#34;&gt;中文版本&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;div&#xA;  class=&#34;link-card group relative my-3 w-full overflow-hidden rounded-xl border border-[var(--lc-border,rgba(15,23,42,0.12))] bg-[var(--lc-bg,var(--card-bg,var(--surface,#ffffff))))] transition-shadow duration-150 hover:shadow-[var(--lc-shadow-hover,0_14px_30px_-18px_rgba(15,23,42,0.35))]&#34;&#xA;  data-url=&#34;https://www.paulgraham.com/talk.html&#34;&#xA;&gt;&#xA;  &lt;a&#xA;    class=&#34;link-card__fallback block px-4 py-3 text-sm font-medium text-[var(--lc-url,var(--link-color,#0e6a85))] underline-offset-4 hover:underline&#34;&#xA;    href=&#34;https://www.paulgraham.com/talk.html&#34;&#xA;    target=&#34;_blank&#34;&#xA;    rel=&#34;noopener&#34;&#xA;  &gt;&#xA;    https://www.paulgraham.com/talk.html&#xA;  &lt;/a&gt;&#xA;&lt;/div&gt;&#xA;&#xA;&lt;h1 id=&#34;write-like-you-talk&#34;&gt;Write Like You Talk&lt;/h1&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;October 2015&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Here&amp;rsquo;s a simple trick for getting more people to read what you write: write in spoken language.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;Something comes over most people when they start writing. They write in a different language than they&amp;rsquo;d use if they were talking to a friend. The sentence structure and even the words are different. No one uses &amp;ldquo;pen&amp;rdquo; as a verb in spoken English. You&amp;rsquo;d feel like an idiot using &amp;ldquo;pen&amp;rdquo; instead of &amp;ldquo;write&amp;rdquo; in a conversation with a friend.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Write Simply</title>
      <link>https://linguage.github.io/paul_graham/essays_en/simply/</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://linguage.github.io/paul_graham/essays_en/simply/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;→ &lt;a href=&#34;https://linguage.github.io/paul_graham/essays_zh/simply/&#34;&gt;中文版本&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;div&#xA;  class=&#34;link-card group relative my-3 w-full overflow-hidden rounded-xl border border-[var(--lc-border,rgba(15,23,42,0.12))] bg-[var(--lc-bg,var(--card-bg,var(--surface,#ffffff))))] transition-shadow duration-150 hover:shadow-[var(--lc-shadow-hover,0_14px_30px_-18px_rgba(15,23,42,0.35))]&#34;&#xA;  data-url=&#34;https://www.paulgraham.com/simply.html&#34;&#xA;&gt;&#xA;  &lt;a&#xA;    class=&#34;link-card__fallback block px-4 py-3 text-sm font-medium text-[var(--lc-url,var(--link-color,#0e6a85))] underline-offset-4 hover:underline&#34;&#xA;    href=&#34;https://www.paulgraham.com/simply.html&#34;&#xA;    target=&#34;_blank&#34;&#xA;    rel=&#34;noopener&#34;&#xA;  &gt;&#xA;    https://www.paulgraham.com/simply.html&#xA;  &lt;/a&gt;&#xA;&lt;/div&gt;&#xA;&#xA;&lt;h1 id=&#34;write-simply&#34;&gt;Write Simply&lt;/h1&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;March 2021&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;I try to write using ordinary words and simple sentences.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;That kind of writing is easier to read, and the easier something is to read, the more deeply readers will engage with it. The less energy they expend on your prose, the more they&amp;rsquo;ll have left for your ideas.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Writing and Speaking</title>
      <link>https://linguage.github.io/paul_graham/essays_en/speak/</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://linguage.github.io/paul_graham/essays_en/speak/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;→ &lt;a href=&#34;https://linguage.github.io/paul_graham/essays_zh/speak/&#34;&gt;中文版本&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;div&#xA;  class=&#34;link-card group relative my-3 w-full overflow-hidden rounded-xl border border-[var(--lc-border,rgba(15,23,42,0.12))] bg-[var(--lc-bg,var(--card-bg,var(--surface,#ffffff))))] transition-shadow duration-150 hover:shadow-[var(--lc-shadow-hover,0_14px_30px_-18px_rgba(15,23,42,0.35))]&#34;&#xA;  data-url=&#34;https://www.paulgraham.com/speak.html&#34;&#xA;&gt;&#xA;  &lt;a&#xA;    class=&#34;link-card__fallback block px-4 py-3 text-sm font-medium text-[var(--lc-url,var(--link-color,#0e6a85))] underline-offset-4 hover:underline&#34;&#xA;    href=&#34;https://www.paulgraham.com/speak.html&#34;&#xA;    target=&#34;_blank&#34;&#xA;    rel=&#34;noopener&#34;&#xA;  &gt;&#xA;    https://www.paulgraham.com/speak.html&#xA;  &lt;/a&gt;&#xA;&lt;/div&gt;&#xA;&#xA;&lt;h1 id=&#34;writing-and-speaking&#34;&gt;Writing and Speaking&lt;/h1&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;March 2012&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;I&amp;rsquo;m not a very good speaker. I say &amp;ldquo;um&amp;rdquo; a lot. Sometimes I have to pause when I lose my train of thought. I wish I were a better speaker. But I don&amp;rsquo;t wish I were a better speaker like I wish I were a better writer. What I really want is to have good ideas, and that&amp;rsquo;s a much bigger part of being a good writer than being a good speaker.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
